<article>
    <h1>Hougang THE BAD</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201206/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-06"><time>2020-12-06</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FEATURES</span>
        - <span role="byline">Olivia Ho</span>
    </section>

    <p>DU­RA­TION AND DIF­FI­CULTY</p>
    <p>Three hours and 20 min­utes, about 16,500 steps and two bus rides (three to four stops each). Mod­er­ately easy walk.</p>
    <p>HIGH­LIGHTS</p>
    <p>Ra­makr­ishna Mis­sion; Tian Kong and Kan­ca­narama Bud­dhist Tem­ple; Zi Yun Kai Ji Gong; Chee Tong Tem­ple; Neo Kian Guan Con­fec­tionery & Cakes; Rain­bow Block 316; Church of the Na­tiv­ity of the Blessed Vir­gin Mary; Masjid Haji Yu­soff; Hougang Tou Mu Kung; Ah Seah Teochew Por­ridge; Paya Le­bar Methodist Church</p>
    <p>THE GOOD</p>
    <p>Hougang is the new­est trail on the block, hav­ing been launched in Oc­to­ber.</p>
    <p>There are three short trails: Land­marks Of Hougang,</p>
    <p>Ar­chi­tec­tural Gems and In­sti­tu­tions Of Ser­vice.</p>
    <p>Feel­ing am­bi­tious, I com­bined all three, start­ing at Ra­makr­ishna Mis­sion near Bart­ley MRT, mov­ing north-east to­wards Up­per Paya Le­bar Road, then walk­ing in a large loop, fin­ish­ing at Paya Le­bar Methodist Church near Seran­goon MRT.</p>
    <p>High­lights i nclude t he Tian Kong and Kan­ca­narama Bud­dhist Tem­ple, which houses both Taoist and Thai Bud­dhist tem­ples, adorned by in­tri­cate gold</p>
    <p>en­grav­ings hand-carved by the res­i­dent head monk over more than a decade.</p>
    <p>In­sta­gram­mers will be de­lighted with Block 316 Hougang Av­enue 7, with its sweep­ing rain­bow mu­ral that dates back to the 1980s.</p>
    <p>Should you re­quire for­ti­fy­ing on your trek, pick up some tra­di­tional pas­tries from Neo Kian Guan Con­fec­tionery, founded in 1932, or stop for the ar­ray of dishes at the 56-year-old Ah Seah Teochew Por­ridge.</p>
    <p>Stops are quite spaced out; I ended up tak­ing the bus twice. If you do not have three hours to spare, do just one of the short trails.</p>
    <p>De­tours to spots like Tua Jia Kar are not worth it. It is not even the orig­i­nal vil­lage well, but a com­mem­o­ra­tive replica put up in 2005.</p>
    <p>Due to Covid-19, some places of wor­ship, like Chee Tong Tem­ple, are not open to the pub­lic. The Church of the Na­tiv­ity of the Blessed Vir­gin Mary is un­der­go­ing ren­o­va­tion.</p>
    <p>MORE STO­RIES on C4-6</p>

